<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>in pain • in pains</xh5><p> <i>in pain—</i>suffering physical pain or discomfort caused by injury or disease: They lay rolling themselves on the ground, heavily groaning <u>in pain</u>.</p><p> <i>in pains—</i>1. <i>(of a woman)</i> in the throes of childbirth: I remember that in the film, the husband of the woman <u>in pains</u> was sitting far from the scene. 2. <i>= in pain: </i>She saw herself test it on a criminal—a rapist, and she saw how much he was <u>in pains</u>. 3. <i>(followed by Infinitive)</i> making a particular effort to do smth.: He was <u>in pains</u> to stress that the main task of government was the defense of the rich against the poor.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> The expression does not fully correlate in meaning with the phrase <b>at pains</b>—<i><b>=</b> in pains 3:</i> Linda was <u>at pains</u> to see that no one was left out.</p> </entry>
